---
import LabLayout from "../../layouts/LabLayout.astro";

const title = "About | The AI Runtime Lab";
const description =
  "What a field report is, and the lifecycle every field report moves through, from question to outcome.";

const lifecycle = [
  "Question",
  "Hypothesis",
  "Experiment",
  "Evaluation",
  "Reliability",
  "Production Trial",
  "Outcome",
];
---

<LabLayout title={title} description={description} ogType="article">
  <article class="lab-container about reading">
    <header class="about__head">
      <p class="mono-label" style="color: var(--accent)">About the Lab</p>
      <h1>An engineering notebook that became public.</h1>
    </header>

    <section aria-labelledby="what-heading">
      <h2 id="what-heading">What a field report is</h2>
      <p>
        A forward-deployed engineer embeds with a customer to scope, build, and
        deploy production software inside that customer's environment. The role
        was pioneered at Palantir and is now how OpenAI, Anthropic, and others
        ship AI into real operations. The Lab is the engineering arm of The AI
        Runtime, and a field report runs that same method in public.
      </p>
      <p>
        The work that separates it from a consultant or a demo: ship a
        production system, not a slide deck, and stay on it until it runs
        reliably under the real constraints. Out-of-the-box rarely survives
        first contact with a customer's data, budget, and edge cases. A
        field report starts from a real customer-shaped problem, scopes the
        problem behind the stated ask, sets a reliability bar, builds the
        smallest system that can hold it, and publishes the failures, evals,
        decisions, and the final outcome.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each one is scoped like an engagement: an industry, a customer, the ask,
        the engineering question, the reliability bar, and an explicit line
        between what is in scope and what is declined.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="replicate-heading">
      <h2 id="replicate-heading">Built to be replicated</h2>
      <p>
        The part of forward-deployed work that compounds is not the one-off
        build, it is what happens after: spot the patterns that recur across
        problems and generalize them into a repeatable method. That is the point
        here too. The reliability bar, the eval harness, the decision records,
        and the code are portable, so the next problem starts from a method, not
        a blank page.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="cadence-heading">
      <h2 id="cadence-heading">Updated weekly</h2>
      <p>
        Field reports are live records, not finished essays. Each one advances
        on a weekly cadence: a stage moves forward, a measurement lands, a
        decision gets recorded. The progress timeline on each field report
        shows which of the stages below is done, in progress, or still ahead,
        and the field log captures what changed and when.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="lifecycle-heading">
      <h2 id="lifecycle-heading">The lifecycle</h2>
      <p>Every field report moves through the same stages, in order:</p>
      <ol class="lifecycle">
        {lifecycle.map((stage, i) => (
          <li class="lifecycle__step">
            <span class="lifecycle__num">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
            <span class="lifecycle__label">{stage}</span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
      <p class="about__note">
        Each field report also carries a status label for a quick read:
        <strong>investigating</strong>, <strong>in-eval</strong>, or
        <strong>published</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="reading-heading">
      <h2 id="reading-heading">Further reading on FDE</h2>
      <p>If the role is new to you, these explain it well:</p>
      <ul class="links">
        <li>
          <a href="https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/forward-deployed-engineers" rel="noopener">
            The Pragmatic Engineer
          </a>, what forward-deployed engineers are and why demand is rising.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://blog.palantir.com/a-day-in-the-life-of-a-palantir-forward-deployed-software-engineer-45ef2de257b1" rel="noopener">
            Palantir
          </a>, a day in the life of a forward-deployed software engineer.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://builtin.com/articles/forward-deployed-engineers" rel="noopener">
            Built In
          </a>, how FDEs turn field patterns into product.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="more-heading">
      <h2 id="more-heading">More from The AI Runtime</h2>
      <p>
        The Lab is one arm of The AI Runtime, the community and publication for
        engineers shipping AI to production.
      </p>
      <ul class="links">
        <li><a href="https://theairuntime.com" rel="noopener">theairuntime.com</a>, the publication.</li>
        <li><a href="https://theairuntime.com/subscribe" rel="noopener">Subscribe to the newsletter</a> for new field reports.</li>
        <li><a href="/field-lab/">The Field Lab</a>, a library of production-shaped build problems.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</LabLayout>

<style>
  .about { padding: 3.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .about__head { margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
  .about__head h1 { margin-top: 0.8rem; }

  .lifecycle { list-style: none; margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 0; display: grid; gap: 0.4rem; }
  .lifecycle__step {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
    padding: 0.7rem 1rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    background: var(--bg-2);
  }
  .lifecycle__num { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--accent); }
  .lifecycle__label { font-family: var(--font-mono); color: var(--text); letter-spacing: -0.01em; }
  .about__note { color: var(--text-2); }

  .links { padding-left: 1.2rem; }
  .links li { margin: 0.4em 0; }
</style>
